<subSubSection pageId="78" pageNumber="79" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="78.[151,1437,1651,2002]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1831,1857]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species was described from Honshu, 
<collectingCountry box="[815,879,1832,1858]" name="Japan" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Japan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Takeuchi, K." box="[896,1067,1831,1857]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" pagination="173 - 229" refId="ref80448" refString="Takeuchi, K. (1938) A systematic study on the suborder Symphyta (Hymenoptera) of the Japanese Empire (1). Tenthredo, 2, 173 - 229." type="journal article" year="1938">Takeuchi 1938</bibRefCitation>
) and later recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[1368,1436,1832,1858]" name="South Korea" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Korea</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[159,342,1867,1893]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" pagination="99 - 116" refId="ref76721" refString="Shinohara, A. (2001) The group of Pamphilius sylvaticus (Hymenoptera, Pamphiliidae): Two new species, new collection records, and a key to Palearctic species. Japanese Journal of Systematic Entomology, 7, 99 - 116." type="journal article" year="2001">Shinohara 2001</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A. &amp; Tripotin, P." box="[355,682,1867,1893]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" pagination="196 - 201" refId="ref78956" refString="Shinohara, A. &amp; Tripotin, P. (2021 b) Collection records of Pamphiliidae and Xiphydriidae (Hymenoptera) from Korea, with notes on Xiphydria jakovlevi. Japanese Journal of Systematic Entomology, 27, 196 - 201." type="journal article" year="2021">Shinohara &amp; Tripotin 2021b</bibRefCitation>
). The larvae are oligophagous solitary leaf-rollers on 
<taxonomicName box="[1294,1387,1867,1893]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Aruncus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1294,1387,1867,1893]" italics="true" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Aruncus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[151,238,1903,1929]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Spiraea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,238,1903,1929]" italics="true" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Spiraea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[256,365,1903,1929]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
) in 
<collectingCountry box="[414,478,1904,1930]" name="Japan" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Japan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A. &amp; Kameda, Y. &amp; Kojima, H." box="[495,764,1903,1929]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" pagination="123 - 131" refId="ref78110" refString="Shinohara, A., Kameda, Y. &amp; Kojima, H. (2016 b) Pamphilius daisenus, an oligophagous sawfly feeding on Spiraea japonica: The first record of Pamphiliidae (Hymenoptera) associated with Spiraea. Bulletin of the National Museum of Nature and Science, Tokyo, Series A, 42, 123 - 131." type="journal article" year="2016">
Shinohara 
<emphasis box="[621,680,1903,1929]" italics="true" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">et al.</emphasis>
2016b
</bibRefCitation>
). Molecular data are not available from the Korean specimens, but the eight COI sequences from the Japanese material formed a clade which was sister to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shinohara" authorityYear="1985" box="[1269,1384,1939,1965]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[1269,1384,1939,1965]" italics="true" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">P. gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
